  ('苏州博物馆', 9, 'Taiping Heavenly Kingdom忠王 Mansion', '太平天国忠王府', '', 'https://edwvrriuwzaaqznklrgi.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/cover-images/sub-areas/all/suzhou_museum_sa_10.jpg'),
  ('环秀山庄', 0, 'Yougu Hall (Hall of Abundant Grain)', '有穀堂', '<p>Yougu Hall sits at the front of the entrance axis of Huanxiu Mountain Villa, serving as the first hall visitors encounter, fulfilling both welcoming and ceremonial functions. The name "Yougu" derives from the Analerta, where "gu" carries the dual meaning of virtue and blessing, symbolizing abundance in goodness and fortune. The hall spans three bays with a flush gable roof,通透 on all sides—facing the entrance courtyard to the south and the main pond to the north—serving as the transitional space connecting the front and rear garden areas. The timber frame is finely crafted, the furnishings simple, with a plaque suspended at the center. Though modest in scale, its clear axial relationship creates a dialogue with the main rockery; gazing north from within, Ge Yuliang''s masterpiece comes into full view, establishing the classic "hall facing mountain" layout that defines the garden''s spatial structure.</p>', 'https://edwvrriuwzaaqznklrgi.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/cover-images/sub-areas/all/suzhou_huanxiu_mountain_villa_sa_01.jpg'),
  ('环秀山庄', 1, 'Huanxiu Mountain Villa (Four-Side Hall)', '环秀山庄（四面厅）', '<p>The Four-Side Hall is situated north of the main pond and serves as the garden''s central viewing structure. Spanning five bays with corridors on all four sides and continuous windows on each elevation, it earns its name by offering views in every direction. Facing the pond with Ge Yuliang''s main rockery directly across the water, it is the premier spot for viewing the rockery in its entirety. Though the largest building in the garden, its well-proportioned dimensions maintain an intimate human scale without feeling oppressive. The hall originally bore the plaque "Huanxiu Mountain Villa," from which the garden takes its name. As the visual focal point and spatial hub, visitors can gaze north at the majestic main peak and deep caves, east at the side galleries, west at the towering Hanyun Pavilion, and south at the pond''s reflections, embodying the Suzhou principle of a hall as the eye of the garden with scenery on all sides.</p>', 'https://edwvrriuwzaaqznklrgi.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/cover-images/sub-areas/all/suzhou_huanxiu_mountain_villa_sa_02.png'),
  ('环秀山庄', 2, 'Ge Yuliang Rockery', '戈裕良假山', '<p>The Ge Yuliang Rockery is the soul of Huanxiu Mountain Villa, constructed by the Qing dynasty master Ge Yuliang during the Jiaqing reign. Covering less than half a mu with a main peak exceeding seven meters in height, it creates a majestic landscape of undulating ridges, deep caves, and intersecting ravines, hailed by garden scholar Chen Congzhou as "the crown of Chinese classical garden rockeries." Ge pioneered the "grand axe-cut texture" technique, stacking Lake Tai stones into precipitous cliffs, flying stone bridges, and hidden grottoes with running water beneath. The rockery is fully explorable: stone paths spiral to the summit for panoramic views, while tunnels offer an immersive journey through shifting spatial experiences. It represents the supreme realization of the classical ideal of a garden that is both "tourable and inhabitable," possessing unparalleled artistic and historical value.</p>', 'https://edwvrriuwzaaqznklrgi.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/cover-images/sub-areas/all/suzhou_huanxiu_mountain_villa_sa_03.jpg'),
  ('环秀山庄', 3, 'Hanyun Pavilion (Cloud-Encompassing Pavilion)', '涵云阁', '<p>Hanyun Pavilion stands on the western side of Huanxiu Mountain Villa, a two-story tower built flush against the garden wall. The name "Hanyun" means "encompassing clouds," alluding to its lofty presence. The structure is diminutive yet precisely proportioned, with a masonry ground floor and a timber upper story featuring latticed windows on all sides. As the highest point in the garden, the upper floor offers a bird''s-eye view of the Ge Yuliang Rockery, complementing the ground-level perspective from the Four-Side Hall. Though compact inside, the windows reveal the rockery appearing as a real mountain nearby, while the distant city skyline is borrowed as scenery beyond, showcasing the garden''s masterful manipulation of scale. The pavilion is also the optimal vantage for observing the rockery''s layered composition and stacking technique from the side.</p>', 'https://edwvrriuwzaaqznklrgi.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/cover-images/sub-areas/all/suzhou_huanxiu_mountain_villa_sa_04.jpg'),
  ('环秀山庄', 4, 'Side Building and Corridor', '边楼与边廊', '<p>The Side Building and Corridor run along the eastern wall of Huanxiu Mountain Villa, serving as the connective tissue linking the garden''s various zones. The Side Building is two stories—a corridor below and rooms above—joined with the corridor in a rhythmic high-low sequence. The corridor winds and turns, sometimes hugging the wall, sometimes opening to views, adjusting its path in response to terrain and landscape, embodying the Suzhou principle of "corridors guiding visitors, scenery shifting with every step." Lattice windows and moon gates along the corridor frame views of the rockery, pond, and plantings like a series of landscape paintings unrolled in sequence. The upper floor also provides an elevated vantage for observing the eastern face of the rockery, combining circulation and viewing functions.</p>', 'https://edwvrriuwzaaqznklrgi.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/cover-images/sub-areas/all/suzhou_huanxiu_mountain_villa_sa_05.jpg'),
  ('环秀山庄', 5, 'Wenquan Pavilion (Spring-Inquiring Pavilion)', '问泉亭', '<p>Wenquan Pavilion stands near the Feixue Spring ruins within Huanxiu Mountain Villa, a small square pavilion built specifically for viewing the spring and its surrounding rock-and-water composition. The name "Wenquan" (Inquiring After the Spring) carries refined literati sensibility, personifying the spring with a sense of seeking and inquiry, reflecting the garden owner''s cherishing of and intimacy with the natural water source. The pavilion features a four-sided pyramidal roof on four columns, light and open, blending seamlessly with the adjacent rockery and stone paths. From within, visitors can observe the spring''s outlet and the interplay of water and stone up close, listening to the murmuring flow and appreciating the poetic notion of inquiring how the spring stays so clear. Surrounded by Lake Tai stones and ancient trees, it is one of the most serene rest stops in the garden.</p>', 'https://edwvrriuwzaaqznklrgi.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/cover-images/sub-areas/all/suzhou_huanxiu_mountain_villa_sa_06.png'),
  ('环秀山庄', 6, 'Buqiu Studio (Autumn-Compensating Studio)', '补秋舫', '<p>Buqiu Studio is located east of the main rockery within Huanxiu Mountain Villa, a land-boat structure representing a common Suzhou garden archetype. The front mimics a prow, the rear corridor suggests a stern, and the central cabin features latticed windows on both sides, the whole resembling a painted pleasure boat moored among rocks. The name "Buqiu" (Compensating for Autumn) implies that this spot makes up for any insufficiency in autumn scenery, reflecting the owner''s fondness for autumn colors. The studio faces the eastern foot of the rockery, where autumn maples blaze against the yellow-stone rocks in a riot of color, fulfilling the "buqiu" aspiration. The land-boat form satisfies viewing needs while the nautical imagery evokes water and reverie, bringing the delight of boating to a waterless setting, exemplifying the Suzhou technique of substituting meaning for scenery and interweaving the real and the imagined.</p>', 'https://edwvrriuwzaaqznklrgi.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/cover-images/sub-areas/all/suzhou_huanxiu_mountain_villa_sa_07.jpg'),
  ('环秀山庄', 7, 'Bantan Qiushui Yifangshan Pavilion (Half-Pond Autumn Water and One-Room Mountain Pavilion)', '半潭秋水一房山亭', '<p>Bantan Qiushui Yifangshan Pavilion crowns the summit of the main rockery, the highest viewing point in Huanxiu Mountain Villa. The highly poetic name derives from Song dynasty verse: "half a pond of autumn water" refers to the pool seen below, and "one room of mountain" describes the rocks surrounding the pavilion, seamlessly fusing location and vista. The hexagonal pavilion is diminutive, accommodating only a few, perched on the main peak with eaves like wings ready to take flight. Reaching it requires spiraling up steep, narrow stone paths through deep grottoes, culminating in a sudden panoramic revelation. From within, the entire garden—pond, rockery, and architecture—unfolds below, with the half-pond at its foot and rocks filling the view, perfectly matching its name. It is the ultimate vantage for experiencing Ge Yuliang''s art of "vast mountains in a miniature space" and the most poetically evocative spot in the garden.</p>', 'https://edwvrriuwzaaqznklrgi.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/cover-images/sub-areas/all/suzhou_huanxiu_mountain_villa_sa_08.jpg'),
  ('环秀山庄', 8, 'Feixue Spring Ruins', '飞雪泉遗址', '<p>The Feixue Spring Ruins lie at the southwestern foot of the rockery in Huanxiu Mountain Villa, marking the site of the garden''s most important historical water source. Named for its spray resembling flying snow, the spring once yielded clear, cold water that fed the streams running through the rockery, contributing to the villa''s name. When Ge Yuliang constructed the rockery during the Qing dynasty, he channeled this spring to the summit, creating a cascade that tumbled through the rocks, animating the rockery with the dynamic interplay of mountain and water. Though the spring has since run dry, the surrounding rockwork, pool walls, and stone channels remain intact, allowing visitors to imagine the former spectacle of cascading water. The ruins, with their craggy Lake Tai stones, ancient vines, and mottled moss, exude a beauty of desolate antiquity—a place to contemplate the passage of time and the garden''s historical transformation.</p>', 'https://edwvrriuwzaaqznklrgi.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/cover-images/sub-areas/all/suzhou_huanxiu_mountain_villa_sa_09.jpg'),
